<HL>
   Hong Kong to Expand Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   HONG KONG -- Hong Kong will expand its fledgling Exchange
Fund bill program to include treasury instruments that are
longer than 13 weeks in duration, David Nendick, the colony's
secretary for monetary affairs, said.
   Mr. Nendick said that he is pleased with the dozen weekly
auctions of the tax-free bills to date, but that some changes
will be made after the initial program ends next Tuesday. "To
enhance the effectiveness of the bills as money market
instruments, bills of other maturities up to 12 months may be
issued additionally from time to time," he said. The
government began auctioning off the 13-week bills in
mid-March to provide a mechanism to adjust liquidity in the
system. About 3.5 billion Hong Kong dollars (US$444.9
million) of bills have been offered in HK$300 million
installments.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong has had a steady stream of budget surpluses, so
it doesn't need to rely on treasury debt issues for fiscal
reasons. The auctions for Exchange Fund bills have found a
steady local appetite and are regularly oversubscribed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0168
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0168.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Economic Data
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- Canada's gross domestic product rose 0.1% in
March as a result of an increase in output of goods-producing
industries, Statistics Canada, a federal agency, said.
   The increase followed a 0.1% gain in February and a 0.1%
decline in January. In the first quarter, the figure rose
0.2%. It reflects the total value of the country's output of
goods and services.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In March, output of goods rose 0.2% partly because of a
pickup in the production of autos and auto parts. Output of
the services industry remained unchanged.
   Separately, the Canadian Conference Board reported that
its index of business confidence fell in the first quarter to
its lowest level since 1983. The board's survey was conducted
in mid-March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0167
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0167.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Salomon Offers Warrants
   In Play on Belgian Shares
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   SB B.CMT B.DEF B.PET B.SOL B.BBL
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- Salomon Inc. offered a novel way for investors
to bet on a rise in Belgian share prices without the
complications of dealing on the Brussels Bourse.
   The New York-based investment banking firm offered 500,000
warrants representing a basket of six blue-chip Belgian
shares at 283 Belgian francs ($8.17) each, or a total of 142
million Belgian francs ($4.1 million). Such share warrants
have proliferated in several other European countries in
recent years, but bankers here said they believed Salomon's
issue was the first of its kind in Belgium.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Each 100 warrants represents the current value of two
shares of Barco N.V., one of Bekaert N.V., one of S.A.
Cimenteries CBR, four of Delhaize "Le Lion" S.A. Belgium,
three of Petrofina S.A. and two of Solvay &amp; Cie. Based on
yesterday's share prices, the warrants are priced at a
premium of 18.6%. That means that, if the warrant is held for
its full 18-month life, the value of the underlying shares
would have to rise at least 18.6% to make it profitable for
holders.
   The warrants can be exercised from June 29, 1990, through
Nov. 29, 1991. They will be listed on the London and
Luxembourg stock exchanges. The issue is being distributed by
Salomon's London investment banking unit as well as Dumenil
Leble Bank (Belgium) S.A. and Banque Bruxelles Lambert S.A.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
