<HL>
   Net at Software
   Toolworks Surged
   During 4th Period
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CANNY TWRX
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHATSWORTH, Calif. -- Software Toolworks Inc. said net
income more than tripled in its fourth quarter ended March
31, bolstered by its recent acquisition of Mindscape Inc. and
strong sales of computer game products.
   The maker of entertainment, educational and office
software said net rose to $2.3 million, or 12 cents a share,
from $740,000, or five cents a share, a year earlier.
Per-share amounts are adjusted for a 2-for-1 split paid April
4.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The latest period includes an after-tax charge of $1.2
million related to costs of the Mindscape acquisition and
$677,000 in tax credits for previous losses.
   Revenue jumped 78% in the quarter, to $21.9 million from
$12.3 million. Shares outstanding averaged 20.3 million in
the latest period, compared with 16 million a year earlier.
   The company acquired Mindscape on March 15 in a stock swap
valued at about $40 million. Because the transaction is being
accounted for under the pooling-of-interests method, the
latest period's results as well as the earlier ones include
those of Mindscape, a company official said.
   Mindscape, based in Northbrook, Ill., has a license to
produce game cartridges for Nintendo Co. computer game
system. Software Toolworks said its latest results were
boosted by the company's release of an "Infiltrator" game for
the Nintendo system as well as sales of older game products
including "Paperboy," "Road Blaster" and "The Hunt for Red
October."
   Software Toolworks said it signed a letter of intent with
Canon Inc. of Japan to develop software for the Canon
Navigator IBM-compatible personal computer to be released
this year.
   For the year ended March 31, Software Toolworks' net was
$2.5 million, or 14 cents a share. It had a net loss of $4.3
million, or 29 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue swelled
96% to $68.7 million from $35.0 million. Average shares
outstanding, adjusted for the 2-for-1 split, rose to 18.3
million from 14.8 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0158
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0158.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Bush Sniffs a Deal,
   But I Smell a Trap
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   In Paul A. Gigot's May 11 Potomac Watch column, "The
President Sniffs Out a Budget Deal," he wrote of the belly
laughs that talk of a line-item veto and other significant
budget reforms invokes inside the Washington Beltway. Well,
I'm holding my stomach after reading Mr. Gigot's column, not
from laughter, but from that sinking feeling one gets when he
realizes disaster has just about hit. When so astute an
observer as Mr. Gigot is tempted to give serious credence to
the seductive offer of deals by the big spenders and taxers,
one has to worry that the Washington virus of wishful
thinking has reached epidemic proportions. The budget
"reforms" now dangled before the president are nothing more
than fig leafs offered to a man being asked to humiliate
himself.
   None of the big spenders and taxers are talking about true
budget reform such as constitutional line-item-veto authority
and a balanced-budget/tax-limitation constitutional
amendment. (If the president is serious about wanting a
line-item veto, why doesn't he go ahead and exercise the
line-item-veto authority he professes to believe the
Constitution already grants the president?)
</LP>
<TEXT>
   None of the taxers and spenders are talking about
returning the Social Security surplus to taxpayers -- to end
the current dishonest practice of diverting Social Security
taxes to pay for general government spending -- and extending
Gramm-Rudman through 1999 to make up the lost revenues by
restraining spending growth. All we see so far are flimsy
proposals to enhance presidential rescission authority with a
simple majority-rule congressional override provision and
dangerous balanced-budget requirements with impotent "tax
notification" provisions that would increase the
already-substantial bias toward raising taxes.
   The administration is playing a very dangerous game by
tantalizing Congress with the suggestion that it is willing
to trade large tax increases for budget-process reform.
Bush's boys easily could blunder into a situation when they
trap the president into a corner and he is forced to trade
off tax increases against superficial budget-process reform.
Then we can all hold our noses with one hand as we sniff the
deal and hold our stomachs with the other hand, and, again,
it won't be from laughter.
   Lawrence A. Hunter
   Deputy Chief Economist
   U.S. Chamber of Commerce
   Washington
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0157
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0157.
</DOCID>
