<HL>
   Luxembourg's Bank of Credit to Close
   Most U.S. Operations Amid New Probes
   ----
   By John J. Fialka
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Hounded by two new investigations and under
increasing pressure from the Federal Reserve, the Bank of
Credit &amp; Commerce International is planning to close most of
its U.S. operations.
   An internal status report prepared by B.A. Palkhiwala,
general manager of the Luxembourg-based bank's U.S. branches,
said that its problems include a large batch of "classified
loans," or loans of questionable value. The report added that
these loans will complicate "contingency plans" of the once
fast-growing bank to close its Florida and California offices
and consolidate operations in its New York City office. A
copy of the report was obtained by The Wall Street Journal.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The report said the New York office is being investigated
by the district attorney's office in Manhattan, which has
issued subpoenas for records of six accounts. It added that
there is a separate investigation under way by federal
prosecutors in Miami that poses a "very serious danger" of a
new indictment against the bank and some of its U.S.
officers.
   A statement issued yesterday from BCCI's London
headquarters said that Mr. Palkhiwala's report presented a
limited view of the reorganization alternatives being
considered and that it represented Mr. Palkhiwala's views and
not necessarily those of the bank. BCCI, which has $21
billion of assets, added that it has more than enough assets
to cover classified loans and that it is "completely
confident" it won't be indicted in Miami.
   Earlier this year, BCCI pleaded guilty to an indictment
accusing it of drug-related, money-laundering charges brought
by U.S. prosecutors in Tampa, Fla. According to federal
officials, BCCI is one of the targets of a separate
investigation under way in Miami that is examining why the
bank temporarily injected $25 million into CenTrust Bank of
Miami in 1988 at a time when federal examiners were
questioning CenTrust's soundness.
   CenTrust went into receivership in March and is expected
to cost U.S. taxpayers about $2 billion. BCCI attorneys have
said there was nothing illegal about the transaction.
   The report stated that Zafar Iqbal, who is head of the
management reorganization committee for BCCI's new owners in
Abu Dhabi, will meet this month with Federal Reserve
officials in New York and Washington who have been applying
"pressure" to meet with a top BCCI official.
   The bank currently is working on plans to close offices in
Miami, Los Angeles and San Francisco. The report said that
these plans are complicated by a bad-loan portfolio that the
Federal Reserve has said can't be transferred to another
branch within the U.S. "The substantial portfolio of
classified loans," the report stated, "will need handling in
order to prevent massive write-offs."
   In its statement from London, BCCI said that $29 million
of its $152 million loan portfolio in Miami is classified --
which is banking jargon for loans that may not be repaid in
full. The bank said a recent infusion of more than $600
million is "more than adequate" to cover any losses, both in
Miami and elsewhere. Mr. Palkhiwala's report noted that
federal and state regulators are concerned that BCCI records
may be destroyed or lost during a consolidation. It suggested
that all records be microfilmed and kept in a central
repository.
   A spokesman for the New York district attorney's office
said it could neither confirm nor deny that it was
investigating BCCI's New York office, which runs most of the
bank's U.S. operations.
   In April, BCCI announced it was being reorganized after a
large cash infusion from Sheik Zayed al-Nahyan, president of
the United Arab Emirates and the ruler of oil-rich Abu Dhabi.
Previously it had been controlled by a group of Pakistani
bankers in London who experienced large losses in 1989 as the
result of unsecured or poorly collateralized loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0148
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0148.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Lobbyists Against Noise Pollution
   Pick Up Some Unexpected Allies
   ----
   By Gary Lamphier
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   SLCPC
</CO>
<LP>
   It may be sweet music to Judy Hawkins's ears, but to
teen-agers who use her 7-Eleven store in downtown Victoria,
British Columbia, as a meeting place, the music that blares
through outdoor speakers is twisted, sister.
   "I try not to pay attention to it," says 16-year-old John
Ark, hanging out in front of the store. Adds friend Paul
Upjohn, 18: "It's like standing in an elevator. It makes me
feel like kicking in the windows." Shelly Lang, 16, says, "A
lot of kids bring ghetto blasters" to try and drown it out.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The scathing music reviews suit Ms. Hawkins just fine.
Hers is one of 10 7-Eleven convenience stores in British
Columbia that use tunes teens find offensive to keep them
from loitering nearby, plugging up parking lots and scaring
off potential customers.
   The programmed music, which the store buys monthly from a
local distributor, goes by the name the Golden Sound. It's
heavy on light, meandering instrumentals by artists such as
Ray Conniff and Mantovani.
   "It's all the music that kids hate, stuff like `Moon
River,' " says Tom Wolnicki, a 7-Eleven supervisor who helped
Ms. Hawkins install her sound system in April.
   Ms. Hawkins says the bad vibes quickly vexed the
loiterers. "The after-school crowd {used to be} anywhere from
15 to 20 kids" who would loiter outside her store, slurping
Slurpees or crunching candy. "Now, it's just five or six" who
can stomach the music. And they don't linger long.
   "When I see half a dozen kids gathering, that's when my
antennae turn up," along with the sound volume, says Ms.
Hawkins. But "it's not as if, boom, they're gone. It usually
takes three or four minutes" for the noxious notes to do
their work.
   A spokeswoman at the Dallas headquarters of Southland
Corp., 7-Eleven's parent, says the 7,000-store chain is "real
excited" about using the anti-loitering scheme elsewhere. To
date, she says, it's being used only by the 7-Eleven stores
in British Columbia. "Maybe we could even elevate it to
orchestra or chamber music," the spokeswoman adds.
   Jerry Reske, vice president of Pacific Sound Inc. in
Seattle, which sells the Golden Sound in the Northwest, says
he isn't surprised by its use as teen repellent. People like
different kinds of music, he says, and "for teen-agers, it's
a downer. . . . I've done programming to {drive teens away
from} a number of carwashes."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0147
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0147.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Bigotry by Implication
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   Julie Salamon's review of the movie "Longtime Companion"
(Leisure &amp; Arts, May 10), while positive in general overview,
harbored underlying prejudices that I found disturbing. The
implication that homosexuals are other than familiar and
likable, and that they live on the fringe, serves only to
emphasize the point that society seeks to isolate those
largely affected by acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   It is precisely this bigoted attitude that promotes
superficial judgment and obliterates one of the major health
concerns in this country. It is unfortunate that more
deliberate attention will not be made toward conquering this
fatal disease until it either begins to ravage the
heterosexual population or until heterosexuals begin to
accept the fact that homosexuals do indeed lead respectable,
middle-class lives, no different from their own.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Suzanne Ridge
   Boston
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0146
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0146.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Markets:
   Tokyo Share Prices Advance in Heavy Trading
   As Investors Dismiss Worries Over Weaker Yen
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST JAPAN CANDA EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tokyo stocks finished higher in active trading, as
investors dismissed evidence of the yen weakening and
demonstrated faith in the market's ability to recover,
observers said.
   Meanwhile, London stocks bounced back from their
midafternoon lows to end moderate trading broadly unchanged.
Dealers attributed the recovery purely to Wall Street's
reversal.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo's Nikkei Index of 225 issues gained 204.54 points to
33130.80 yesterday, after rising 108.59 points Wednesday.
   In early trading Friday in Tokyo, the Nikkei index fell
74.24 points to 33056.56.
   Thursday's volume on the first section was estimated at
800 million shares, off slightly from Wednesday. Advancers
outnumbered decliners 612 to 346, while 160 issues were
unchanged.
   According to Mahmoud Ghaemmaghami, manager of research and
a portfolio adviser at WestLB Securities Pacific Ltd.,
forecasts for the market, as well as for the yen, remain
strong.
   "This recovery should continue; not judging by the
Nikkei-Dow alone . . . but looking at the whole market," he
said.
   Indeed, the overall market's strength was evident in
healthy progress on both the Tokyo Stock Price Index of all
issues listed in the first section and the second section
index.
   The Topix advanced 18.65 points, or 0.77%, to 2435.74,
while the second section index gained 35.96 points, or 0.92%,
to 3938.28. The second section index has fallen only two days
since April 26. Volume on the second section was estimated at
17.8 million shares, up from 14.5 million shares.
   Despite a strengthening of the dollar over the yen
yesterday, investors apparently are confident that the yen is
on a firming trend, observers said.
   Much of the dollar's gains have been interpreted as a move
out of Deutsche marks, equity traders said.
   "The dollar has been stronger for the past few days
because of Mr. Bush and Mr. Gorbachev's meetings over arms
cuts," WestLB's Mr. Ghaemmaghami said. "I think this is kind
of a temporary reaction, and the yen should strengthen over
the next couple of weeks."
   Various undervalued sectors -- including shipping,
warehouse, railways, oil and real estate -- firmed as
investors were driven by faith in the market's fundamentals,
participants suggested.
   "The main pillars of strength for the whole market are the
yen and good corporate results" for fiscal 1990, Mr.
Ghaemmaghami said.
   Moreover, investors are shedding fears of yen depreciation
on earnings, with many companies making bullish forecasts for
the current year, he said. And Japan's economy has continued
to expand in terms of gross national product data.
   Speculative groups have also become more active, several
traders noted.
   Strong performers yesterday included many oil companies,
helped by optimism on the yen. Mitsubishi Oil led the sector,
up 100 yen to 1280 yen (66 cents to $8.45).
   Nippon Oil rose 60 yen to 1260 yen and Teikoku Oil rose 40
yen to 1260 yen.
   Tokyu group companies rose again on speculative interest,
stemming from talk that the group's cross-shareholdings are
being increased. Tokyu Corp. soared 120 yen to 1970 yen,
Tokyu Construction added 30 yen to 1350 yen, and Tokyu
Department Store rose 60 yen to 1820 yen.
   Shipbuilders, including Ishikawajima Harima Heavy
Industries, Kawasaki Heavy Industries and Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries, were firmer.
   But most high-technology shares were softer, despite the
implications of a stronger dollar on their export-oriented
businesses.
   Meanwhile, London's performance was volatile, with initial
gains swiftly eroded by profit-taking, futures selling and a
general lack of momentum.
   "The market ran out of steam," said one dealer.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 Share Index ended
down 1.1 points at 2345.1, after falling to a low of 2333.7.
The peak of 2357.2 was reached shortly after the start of
official trading.
   The Financial Times 30 Share Index was down 2.4 points at
1855. Volume was 466.2 million shares, compared with the
556.4 million issues Wednesday.
   Traders generally agreed that, in the near-term, the
market could consolidate recent gains at yet-lower levels.
"It's been too far, too fast," said one trader.
   With London's near-term performance seen hinging on Wall
Street, institutional investors may remain sidelined for a
time. But fund managers are heavily underweighted, traders
noted, suggesting that London could also benefit from their
entry into the market.
   The market generally appears to want to test the upside,
traders said. "Any hint of good news, an acute shortage of
stock, an absence of sellers or a strong Wall Street" will
propel the market upward, said one trader.
   Featured stocks yesterday included Guinness, which gained
27 pence to 769 pence (46 cents to $13.04) on Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton interest, and Enterprise Oil, which rose 34
pence to 663 pence on continued speculation that Elf
Aquitaine will mount a takeover bid.
   Other shares to rise included Bass, which gained 15 pence
to #10.86 on what one trader termed "a good old-fashioned
squeeze." Carlton Communications rose 29 pence to 565 pence
on renewed interest.
   Rolls-Royce rose 6 1/2 pence to 223 1/2 pence on
speculation that something is afoot with the company. Traders
said they couldn't suggest what this may be.
   On the downside, Glaxo eased 12 pence to 785 pence on
concern about competition in the U.S. for that company's
leading products. Traders generally cautioned that stocks
with high dollar earnings may be soon hit by the strong
pound.
   Meanwhile, stocks closed higher in Milan; lower in Paris
and Zurich; and mixed in Frankfurt, Amsterdam and Stockholm.
South African markets were closed for a holiday.
   And prices ended higher in Sydney, Hong Kong, Taipei,
Manila, Wellington and Seoul, and were lower in Singapore.
                                                                                                       

   Here are price trends on the world's major stock markets,
as calculated by Morgan Stanley Capital International
Perspective, Geneva. To make them directly comparable, each
index is based on the close of 1969 equaling 100. The
percentage change is since year-end.
                                                                                                       

                                                 % This
                            May 30     May 29     Year
                                                                                                       

   U.S. .................   332.8      332.5     + 2.4
   Britain ..............   697.6      682.8     - 3.2
   Canada ...............   392.4      388.2     - 9.3
   Japan ................  1363.7     1360.6     -17.6
   France ...............   592.7      593.3     + 4.5
   Germany ..............   296.5      297.7     + 3.9
   Hong Kong ............  2308.1     2273.5     +10.1
   Switzerland ..........   225.4      223.2     + 2.1
   Australia ............   303.9      302.8     - 8.3
   World index ..........   526.4      524.3     - 7.2
</TEXT>
