<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   `Supported' Jobs
   Can Work Wonders
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   Stephen S. Hamilton ("To Educate the Young, Get Them out
of School," editorial page, April 30) observes that most
people learn best by doing something useful with what they
are learning. Without application, school learning fades
rapidly. During the past decade, the Institute for Human
Resource Development and others doing research and practical
work in the field of employment for people with severe mental
retardation and other disabilities have discovered that
"supported employment" works.
   Placing people in jobs and providing the support necessary
for them to learn and stay on the job is much more effective
than training or educating first and then finding a job where
specific retraining is almost always necessary. These
supported-employment programs have proved effective in making
the transition from school to work for this population. Those
concerned with the apprenticeship or partnership programs
recommended by Mr. Hamilton would be well advised to consider
the proven approaches and techniques developed for bringing
people with severe disabilities into the workplace. They can
work for all.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Quincy S. Abbot
   Chairman
   Institute for Human Resource Development
   Glastonbury, Conn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0137
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0137.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   We Respect Dignity
   Of Amnesty-Seekers
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   I was appalled to read in your April 30 page-one article
that students in the English classes for amnesty-seekers in
Dallas were "absorb{ing} little English, but a lot of
humiliation." As an administrator in an English program
approved for amnesty, I speak with authority when I state
that all programs are not run in such a manner as the one you
visited.
   In Illinois all teachers in amnesty programs must be
trained in special workshops and experienced in teaching
English as a second language to adults. The teachers hired
are professionally trained people who respect the dignity and
self-esteem of their students. I agree it is unrealistic to
expect our students to learn English in only 40 hours. We are
attempting to help them gain some survival skills in English
and a basic knowledge of American history and government.
These skills, it is hoped, will enable them to improve their
lives and may even spark an interest in continued education
and in being "politically active in their new homeland," as
immigration attorney Juan Jasso urged them. Our students are
interested and enthusiastic and many continue in our program
long after their 40 hours for legalization are completed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Katharine B. Anderson
   Township High School District 214
   Community Education
   Arlington Heights, Ill.
</TEXT>
