<HL>
   Canadian Dollar Gains
   On Move to Resolve Impasse
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- The Canadian dollar strengthened yesterday on
news that Prime Minister Brian Mulroney will convene a
weekend meeting to address Canada's constitutional impasse.
   The Canadian currency rose in Toronto to 85.30 U.S. cents
from 85 U.S. cents Wednesday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Mulroney summoned the country's 10 provincial premiers
to Ottawa Sunday for negotiations to overcome the
constitutional deadlock. Financial markets interpreted the
announcement as a sign of possible progress toward a
settlement.
   The impasse has renewed demands from some in Quebec for
independence for their largely French-speaking province and
has unsettled Canada's markets.
   The Ottawa meeting follows weeks of intense negotiations
between the federal government and individual provinces that
have narrowed but failed to settle the differences. The
dispute involves proposed constitutional amendments that
which would recognize Quebec as a "distinct society" within
Canada. The accord would also extend new powers to the
provinces.
   Edward Neufeld, executive vice president of the Royal Bank
of Canada, estimated that political uncertainties have pushed
up short-term Canadian interest rates by at least a full
percentage point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0092
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0092.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rembrandt Work Fails
   To Stir Christie's Bidders
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   BID U.CHR
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Art-buying fever was chilly at Christie's
International PLC's auction house, as Rembrandt van Rijn's
"Saint Peter Repentant" failed to find a buyer.
   Bidding stopped at $9.5 million for the 17th-century
masterwork, which had, until recently, hung in the
Metropolitan Museum of Art on loan from its owner. The piece
had been expected to sell for $10 million to $15 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Overall, 43% of the 149 works offered did not sell. The
auction raised $8.1 million, vs. pre-sale expectations of $23
million to $33 million.
   The mediocre results of the Old Masters auction appear to
dash hopes that that type of artwork will be the next "hot"
market now that prices for Impressionist and Modern paintings
seem to be leveling off, based on recent auction results. Art
dealers said concerns about authenticity of many Old Master
paintings are keeping collectors from that slightly more
affordable sector of the market.
   The top lot of the Christie's auction was Pieter Brueghel
the Younger's, "A Peasant Wedding Feast." The colorful 1603
scene sold for $1.4 million, vs. a pre-sale estimate of $1.5
to $2 million.
   Sotheby's Holdings Inc.'s Old Masters paintings sale is
scheduled for today. Up for sale are two views of Venice by
Il Canaletto. The pair is expected to bring about $10
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Slate Signs Up Frankston;
   Software Creators Reunite
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS LOTS
</CO>
<LP>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- Slate Corp., a software start-up
concern, said it hired software developer Robert Frankston
from Lotus Development Corp., in an action that reunites the
creators of VisiCalc, one of the first successful
personal-computer software programs.
   At Slate, Mr. Frankston will be working again with Daniel
Bricklin, the co-developer of VisiCalc. The two started
Software Arts in Mr. Frankston's house in Arlington, Mass.,
in 1979, and developed VisiCalc, the first spreadsheet. The
program helped get business people to start buying Apple
Computer Inc. personal computers, expanding the market beyond
hobbyists. It was later superseded by Lotus Development's
spreadsheet, 1-2-3.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Slate is developing "pen-based software applications" for
a new class of computers that let users enter data by writing
on a screen with a stylus, rather than typing with a
keyboard. People in the industry say Slate is working on
software for note-pad computers that GO Corp., based in
Foster City, Calif., is expected to introduce later this
year.
   Mr. Frankston, 40 years old, had been working on network
computer software at Lotus. He said his title at Slate hasn't
been determined. He added that he will work with Mr.
Bricklin, a Slate co-founder and vice president, in Slate's
Watertown, Mass., offices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
