<HL>
   Former Modulaire
   Chief Is Charged
   In Trading Case
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9B
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission
charged the former chairman and chief executive officer of
Modulaire Industries with insider trading in the company's
1987 acquisition by Waste Management Inc.
   Other defendants charged by the SEC included the wife and
son of Modulaire's president, David Wailes. All defendants,
including former Chairman Joseph Behar, agreed to settle the
case without admitting or denying guilt and will pay a total
of more than $330,000 in penalties and disgorgement of
profit. Mr. Wailes wasn't charged.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The SEC said that on May 7, 1987, Mr. Behar and Mr. Wailes
agreed to have the San Francisco-based supplier of modular
structures acquired by Waste Management at $16 a share. The
stock was selling at about $7 each. After the announcement of
the deal before the market opened on May 11, the share price
jumped to more than $15.
   On May 8, Deborah Castellucci bought 5,400 Modulaire
shares based on nonpublic information given to her by Mr.
Behar, the SEC said. She had been hired by Modulaire two
years earlier to devise a pension plan for the company.
   Meanwhile, Mr. Wailes had been keeping his wife, Adrienne,
apprised of the progress of negotiations, the SEC said; about
8:32 a.m., May 8, he called her from his office. Mrs. Wailes
then began calling friends and relatives "in rapid succession
to tip them to buy Modulaire before the acquisition was
announced," according to the complaint.
   The SEC said Mrs. Wailes called: Dorothy Carter, whose
husband, Donald, bought 4,300 shares; Mary Alice Graves, who
bought 750 shares, and Christopher Scott, who bought 4,200
shares but canceled his purchases before settlement. Dorothy
Carter then spoke to her son-in-law Jon Treder to pass along
the tip, the SEC said. He bought 1,500 shares and his father,
who wasn't charged, bought 750, the agency said.
   The Wailes' son, Deven, who lived with his parents, also
found out about the takeover from his mother and bought 5,000
shares, although he also canceled the order before
settlement.
   Under their settlement agreements, Mr. Behar will disgorge
$43,200, which amounts to Ms. Castellucci's profit. Ms.
Castellucci and Mr. Behar also will each pay a penalty of
$43,200.
   Mrs. Wailes will pay a penalty of $78,130 representing the
profit of the people she allegedly tipped. The Carters will
disgorge and pay a penalty totaling $81,675, including Mr.
Treder's profit. Mr. Treder will pay $30,525 in profit and
penalty, including his father's profit. Ms. Graves will pay a
total $12,375 in disgorgement and penalty.
   Christopher Scott and Deven Wailes have agreed not to
violate securities laws in the future.
   Mr. Behar's attorney, Kurt Mueller, said that by settling,
his client "is neither admitting nor denying guilt. In fact,
he does not admit it." He also said Mr. Behar agreed to
settle because it would cost "far more to litigate this case
than to settle it, not to mention the grief that litigation
would cause."
   Ted Phillips, attorney for Ms. Castellucci, declined to
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Lengthy Slump
   In Commercial
   Realty Is Seen
   ----
   By Christi Harlan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   The commercial real estate market, overbuilt in all
segments during the 1980s, will remain in a recession for the
next five years, according to a survey of 400 real estate
executives.
   The survey results, to be released Monday by the
accounting firm of Ernst &amp; Young, paint a particularly
pessimistic picture of office developments and investment
returns in the New York market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Nationwide, office rents are expected to rise just 2.2% to
2.4% during the first half of the 1990s, in contrast to a
projected inflation rate of about 4.8%.
   "Office {investment} has been the worst-performing sector
for the past two years, and it looks like that's going to
continue to be the worst-performing sector for the next five
years," said Michael L. Evans, national director of Ernst &amp;
Young Real Estate Advisory Services.
   The real estate executives surveyed by Ernst &amp; Young
earlier this year were asked to assess the future markets for
office, warehouse, retail and apartment developments. The
majority of the respondents said value appreciation in all
four categories will lag behind the projected inflation rate,
although apartments and warehouses will come closest to
matching it with projected rent appreciations of 4.5% and
4.1%, respectively.
   Mr. Evans, who led the analysis of the survey results,
said he was struck most by the respondents' negative
assessment of the New York City market and their optimism
about markets in the Southwest, particularly Houston and
Dallas.
   "Clearly Manhattan is at the bottom of the list," he said.
"New York could have some very significant problems."
   Almost one-third of the survey respondents, or 28.6%,
ranked New York as the most overvalued market, followed by
Los Angeles, at 13.8%.
   Houston and Dallas led the list of cities with the most
potential for real estate investment, with positive
assessments by 9.3% and 8.9%, respectively, of the
respondents.
   "It is confirmed that Houston and Dallas are coming back,"
Mr. Evans said. "It's not bottom-fishing. The economics are
there. There was an indication {in the survey} that Houston
and Dallas have reached the place where rents justify the
investment."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
