<HL>
   Commonwealth Edison Is Ordered to Pay
   Over $300 Million in Customer Refunds
   ----
   By James P. Miller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10
</SO>
<CO>
   CWE
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The Illinois Supreme Court ordered Commonwealth Edison Co.
to refund more than $300 million the Chicago utility
collected under an earlier rate increase designed to pay for
three nuclear plants.
   The court also ordered the utility to roll back current
rates to 1988 levels, an action that will cost Commonwealth
about $235 million in revenue annually.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It was the second time in six months the court dealt the
utility a major blow. In December, it ruled Commonwealth
couldn't implement a $245 million rate increase scheduled for
1990.
   The latest order obligates Commonwealth to refund the
approximately $285 million it received under the 1989
increase -- as well as the funds collected to date in 1990.
   The state court found that when the Illinois Commerce
Commission agreed to the rate rises, it "went beyond the
scope of its authority." The court also said the commission's
approval of the rise, which was designed to end a fight
between the utility and various public-interest groups,
represented an "illegal settlement."
   The court remanded the case to the ICC for further
proceedings, including a determination of the exact amounts
to be refunded, and the mechanism for issuing funds to
customers.
   Commonwealth said it hasn't taken any reserve to cover the
refund; an official said the company hasn't yet determined
whether it will take a charge to this year's earnings, or
possibly restate 1989 earnings, or a combination of both.
While the company said it is "committed to protecting our
dividends at current levels," and doesn't currently envision
trimming its payouts, the official said a final determination
won't be made until next month's board meeting.
   Because "it doesn't appear that the legal case has much
life {left} in it," the spokesman said, the utility is
"unlikely" to appeal the matter further. He added, "We're
turning our attention to other avenues of rate relief."
   Commonwealth in April asked state regulators for about
$982 million in rate rises, although it doesn't expect a
response before March 1991. Among the options the company
will now consider, the spokesman said, is a request for an
"emergency interim rate relief" while that request goes
forward, under legal provisions established to help
financially troubled utilities.
   Commonwealth remains mired in regulatory problems
associated with its costly nuclear buildup, under which it
built a total of 12 nuclear plants that now provide 83% of
the utility's generating capacity.
   Its latest request covers expenses associated with its
three newest plants. In addition, it is appealing an August
1989 state court order to repay customers about $250 million
in costs deemed "unreasonable" related to a fourth nuclear
plant.
   Prudential-Bache analyst Barry Abramson said that the
court's order "does create more short-term financial pressure
on the company," but "doesn't alter the longterm financial
picture" for it.
   He thinks the company could "justify the need for the
capacity" for at least a majority of the newest units to
regulators, eventually.
   Aiding such a request, he notes, is the fact that
Commonwealth is "surrounded within a small radius by a dozen
utilities that are going to be impacted by clean-air
legislation," and might find it cheaper to buy Commonwealth's
excess capacity, than to refit their own coal-burning plants.
   Taking into account the rollback and assuming the company
takes a charge in the current year for the refund, Mr.
Abramson is cutting his earnings projection for Commonwealth
to about $1.80 a share from $3.05. But he noted that until
the new plants get some kind of rate coverage, 1990 earnings
"aren't reflective of the company's true earning power."
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday,
Commonwealth shares closed off $1.25, at $31.50.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0057
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0057.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Westinghouse
   Will Buy Back
   20 Million Shares
   ----
   By Gregory Stricharchuk
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   WX EMR SNS
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- Westinghouse Electric Corp. said it will buy
back as many as 20 million common shares, or roughly 7% of
its shares outstanding in the next 12 to 18 months.
   The broadcasting, financial services and power generation
concern also said directors voted to exempt Westinghouse from
the protection of Pennsylvania's anti-takeover law that went
into effect on April 27. The move apparently is aimed at
making Westinghouse stock more attractive to institutional
investors even though the large company isn't considered a
likely takeover target.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, Westinghouse said it sold its combustion
control business to Rosemount Analytical Inc., of
Minneapolis. Terms weren't disclosed. Rosemount is a unit of
Emerson Electric Co., of St. Louis, Mo., a maker of
measurement, control, analytical and valve products.
   Westinghouse also said it is part of a consortium that was
awarded a $358 million contract to build a coal-fired power
generating unit for Old Dominion Electric Cooperative and
Virgina Power. Other members of the consortium are Combustion
Engineering Inc., H.B. Zachry Co. and Black &amp; Veatch
Engineers-Architects.
   The contract calls for a 393-megawatt pulverized coal unit
to be built at the Clover Power Station in Halifax County,
Va.
   Westinghouse stock rose $1.375 to close at $38.375 in
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Analysts who follow the company said the announced
buy-back of more than $700 million of stock all but ends
speculation that Westinghouse might want to launch a bid for
Sundstrand Corp., an aerospace-parts concern based in
Rockford, Ill.
   Westinghouse's top officials have declined to comment
specifically on the Sundstrand rumor. But in a story in this
newspaper earlier this week, the officials cast doubt on
whether Westinghouse would undertake a more than $2 billion
acquisition that would dilute earnings.
   Sundstrand on Wednesday tumbled $4.25. Yesterday the stock
closed at $74, down 12.5 cents in composite trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Westinghouse said it considers its stock an attractive
investment. Initial funding for the buy-back will come from
existing cash, internally generated funds or through the
issuance of short-term debt.
   Separately, the company said it is negotiating a contract
to build and operate a waste-to-energy plant in Waukesha,
Wis.
   The plant will process as many as 600 tons of municipal
solid waste daily to fuel a 20-megawatt power plant. Power
from the plant will be sold to Wisconsin Electric Power Co.
Construction will begin next year with commercial operation
scheduled to begin in early 1994.
   Waukesha County will finance the plant with project
revenue bonds, Westinghouse said.
</TEXT>
