<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Judge Approves Sale
   Of PTL TV Network
   To Morris Cerullo
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. -- A federal bankruptcy judge approved the
sale of the PTL television network for $7 million to Morris
Cerullo World Evangelism, a San Diego-based ministry.
   Morris Cerullo's ministry, which has operations in Canada,
Mexico, Brazil, Britain and the Philippines, among other
sites, also has made a $45 million offer for the balance of
PTL's assets, including 2,200 acres of land, and a hotel and
theme park.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   PTL's founder, Jim Bakker, was convicted of numerous
federal fraud charges in connection with the operations.
   Morris Cerullo World Evangelism said it intends to operate
the complex, known as Heritage Village Church and Missionary
Fellowship Inc., as a family resort. The TV network, it said,
will be run as a 24-hour-a-day, family-oriented, global
satellite network.
   Dennis Shedd, a court-appointed trustee for the PTL
ministry, said the bankruptcy court is expected to consider
the offer for the balance of the estate in about a month,
after proper notice is given to the parties.
   The sale of the network is subject to the approval of the
license transfer by the Federal Communications Commission.
The trustee said the buyer placed $7 million in escrow to
cover the purchase.
   A rival bidder, Oral Roberts University, had offered about
$6.3 million to $6.45 million for the TV network, which
includes production facilities and a satellite lease, Mr.
Shedd said. He added that only Morris Cerullo had made an
offer for the balance of the failed religious empire.
</TEXT>
