<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CHRYSLER NAMED two men to take over the duties of Vice
Chairman Gerald Greenwald, who resigned Wednesday to lead a
proposed employee buy-out of UAL. The two executives, Robert
Miller and Robert Lutz, now appear to be the leading
candidates to eventually succeed Chairman Iacocca.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Nynex was indicted on a criminal contempt charge of
providing information services through a unit, a violation of
the 1982 consent decree that broke up the Bell system. It is
the first such case against a Bell firm.
   ---
   BankAmerica won the bidding contest to take over insolvent
Western S&amp;L, Arizona's second-largest thrift. BankAmerica
will pay $81 million, one of the larger premiums federal
regulators have received in liquidating their inventory of
troubled thrifts.
   ---
   Factory orders plunged 2.3% in April, another sign that
manufacturing remains weak. The decline, led by a 4.3% drop
in durable-goods orders, follows two months of increases.
   ---
   Boeing received an order from China for 33 commercial jets
worth $2 billion with options for 36 more. It is Boeing's
second big order in a week.
   ---
   Coca-Cola is scrapping the much-hyped MagiCan promotion
after only three weeks. The $100 million campaign, the
biggest in Coke's history, was hurt by malfunctioning cans
and a barrage of negative publicity.
   ---
   Capital Cities/ABC announced a plan to limit the audience
guarantees it usually promises advertisers.
   ---
   Ashland Oil was ordered to pay $10.3 million to four
people who claimed fallout from a Kentucky oil refinery had
hurt the quality of their
   ---
   Commonwealth Edison was ordered to refund over $300
million from a rate increase designed to pay for three
nuclear plants. The Chicago utility also has to roll back
rates.
   ---
   Stock prices were mixed as investors took profits in
blue-chips and then bought other stocks. The Dow Jones
industrials closed off 1.90, at 2876.66. Bond prices and the
dollar gained.
                                                                                                       

   Oil prices plunged following a report of higher U.S.
petroleum inventories. U.S. gasoline prices, which led the
recent rally, took the sharpest fall.
   ---
   Corporate buy-backs of junk bonds hit a record $2.5
billion in the first quarter and are expected to set highs
for the year. Traders say the trend helped spur the market's
modest rally.
   ---
   Economic leaders from major industrial nations committed
themselves to reaching a multilateral trade accord this year.
But the officials remained divided on cutting farm subsidies.
   ---
   The Bank of Credit &amp; Commerce plans to close most U.S.
operations. The Luxembourg bank is the focus of two new
investigations and is under growing pressure from the Fed.
   ---
   Saatchi &amp; Saatchi's long-awaited sale of its Hay Group
consulting unit finally appears imminent, though at a price
far below what the firm wanted.
   ---
   Westinghouse plans to buy back up to 7% of its stock.
Directors also voted to exempt the company from
Pennsylvania's new anti-takeover law.
   ---
   Agriculture prices rose 2% in May as strong demand for
pork and tight supplies sent hog prices soaring to their
second-highest level ever.
</TEXT>
