<HL>
   Treasury Suggests
   Home Loan Banks
   Cut Payouts to S&amp;Ls
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Treasury Department recommended that the
Federal Home Loan Bank system consider reducing the dividend
payments it makes to savings and loans because the system may
face some losses on advances to insolvent thrifts.
   Thrift industry groups immediately criticized the
suggestion, arguing that the dividend payments are important
to the struggling industry's earnings. Last year, the home
loan banks paid about $800 million to $900 million in
dividends to solvent thrifts, Martin Regalia, an economist
with the National Council of Savings Institutions estimated,
while those thrifts overall had losses of $86 million for the
year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Clearly the dividends are an important contribution to
keeping the industry healthy," he said. The government is in
the process of closing and selling off hundreds of insolvent
savings and loans. To obtain advances from the home loan
banks, thrifts are required to buy stock in the banks, which,
in turn, pay dividends back to the thrifts.
   The Treasury's suggestion came in a study of
government-sponsored enterprises. Though the home loan banks
haven't lost money on an advance to any thrift, the
department said that "certain banks have exposure to failed
and failing thrifts." The study suggested reducing the
dividend payments to increase the home loan banks' capital or
for establishing a "modest" loan-loss reserve.
   A spokesman for the Federal Housing Finance Board, the
Department of Housing and Urban Development agency that
oversees the home loan bank system, said the need to increase
retained earnings has to be balanced "against the need to
maintain a market rate of return on members' invested
capital."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900601-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900601-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   First Federal Bancorp
   Says Regulators Curb
   Its Lending Activities
</HL>
<DATE>
06/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   FFS
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   PONTIAC, Mich. -- First Federal Bancorp Inc. said the
federal Office of Thrift Supervision has placed strict limits
on the thrift's lending operations because of its inability
to meet new capital requirements.
   First Federal said a group of investors whom it identified
only as current shareholders has offered to infuse $40
million in cash into the company. In return, it said, the
investors want newly issued First Federal shares. The
transaction is designed to enable First Federal's operating
units to meet the federal capital requirements, the thrift
said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, the transaction would "significantly dilute"
current holders' stakes, the company said. First Federal has
3.5 million shares outstanding. The company's stock closed at
$2.25 a share, up 12.5 cents, in American Stock Exchange
composite trading yesterday.
   First Federal said it will continue to explore ways to
improve its capital position, including the possibilities
offered by the cash infusion.
   The restrictions imposed by regulators bar First Federal
from increasing its assets and forbid it to sell or pledge
assets or to make any new loans or investments without prior
U.S. approval. But First Federal may use assets to maintain
adequate liquidity for current obligations, and it may make
certain consumer and home loans.
   The restrictions apply to First Federal's chief operating
subsidiaries, First Federal Savings Bank &amp; Trust, based in
Pontiac, and Citizens Federal Savings Bank, Jacksonville,
Fla.
   Federal authorities imposed the restrictions Wednesday
after First Federal failed to meet new U.S. guidelines for
thrifts' ratios of capital to assets.
   In the quarter ended March 31, First Federal had a loss of
$15.2 million, or $4.20 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
